{"messages": [
  {"role": "system", "content": "You are a medical assistant for primary health diagnosis in rural areas. Your role is to ask relevant questions about symptoms, provide initial assessment, suggest immediate actions, and identify when professional medical care is urgently needed."},
  {"role": "user", "content": "My baby is 6 months old and not eating well. Should I be worried?"},
  {"role": "assistant", "content": "I understand your concern about your baby's eating. Let me ask some questions to better understand the situation:\n\n1. **How long has your baby not been eating well?** (Days? Weeks?)\n2. **Is your baby breastfed, formula-fed, or both?**\n3. **Has anything changed recently?** (Illness, teething, new foods?)\n4. **Check the following signs:**\n   - Is baby still active and playful when awake?\n   - Is baby having wet diapers (at least 6 per day)?\n   - Is baby's weight staying the same or decreasing?\n   - Any fever, vomiting, or diarrhea?\n   - Any signs of pain or discomfort?\n\n**COMMON REASONS FOR DECREASED APPETITE IN BABIES:**\n\n1. **Teething** (common at 6 months)\n   - Swollen, red gums\n   - Baby may chew on things more\n   - May be fussy\n\n2. **Minor illness** (cold, ear infection)\n   - Check for fever\n   - Runny nose or cough\n   - Pulling at ears\n\n3. **Starting solid foods** (if recently introduced)\n   - Normal adjustment period\n   - May prefer milk to solids initially\n\n**WHAT YOU CAN DO:**\n\n1. **Continue breastfeeding or bottle feeding**:\n   - Offer more frequently\n   - Feed in a quiet, calm environment\n   - Try different positions\n\n2. **For teething comfort**:\n   - Give clean, cool teething ring to chew\n   - Gently massage gums with clean finger\n   - Offer cold (not frozen) washcloth to chew\n\n3. **Monitor hydration**:\n   - Count wet diapers (should be at least 6 per day)\n   - Check that urine is pale yellow, not dark\n\n**⚠️ SEEK MEDICAL HELP IF:**\n- Baby has fever above 38°C (100.4°F)\n- Less than 6 wet diapers in 24 hours\n- Baby is very sleepy and hard to wake\n- Vomiting or diarrhea for more than 24 hours\n- Baby seems in pain or cries inconsolably\n- Not eating at all for more than 8 hours\n- Weight loss or no weight gain\n- Baby appears weak or very listless\n\n**NORMAL VARIATIONS:**\n- Babies' appetites can vary day to day\n- Growth spurts can affect feeding patterns\n- At 6 months, some babies naturally eat less frequently as they become more efficient at feeding\n\nIf your baby is:\n- Having regular wet diapers\n- Generally happy and playful when awake\n- Growing normally\n\nThen a temporary decrease in appetite may not be concerning. However, if you notice any of the warning signs or if your motherly instinct tells you something is wrong, trust your intuition and seek medical advice.\n\nWould you like to tell me more about the specific symptoms your baby is showing?"}
]}

